# Yojna Portal - Product Requirements & Architecture

> Single source of truth for the Yojna Portal project. Read this before architecting pages, collections, fields, hooks, or UI. Built on the existing Payload CMS Website Template (Next.js App Router + SQLite + shadcn/ui + Tailwind).

## 1. Product Overview

**Yojna Portal** is a public, blog-style web portal for the **Government of Raipur** that catalogs civic schemes ("yojnas") and publishes related news/updates. It helps citizens discover schemes by category, understand eligibility and benefits, and learn how to apply.

- **Audience:** Raipur citizens (primary), government staff/administrators (content authors), press/partners (secondary).
- **Value:** Turn a scattered list of ~85 schemes into a searchable, categorized, accessible catalog with authoritative scheme detail pages and a news feed.
- **Platform:** Payload CMS (admin + API) with a Next.js App Router front-end. Content authored by Raipur staff in the admin panel; rendered statically with on-demand revalidation.

## 2. Goals & Non-Goals

### Goals
- Catalog every yojna with a consistent, scheme-specific detail page (department, beneficiaries, eligibility, benefits, how to apply, status).
- Browse and filter yojnas by category; full-text search across yojnas and news.
- Government-grade accessibility (WCAG 2.1 AA), mobile-first, fast static pages.
- CMS-managed taxonomy so categories and schemes can change without code edits.
- Bilingual-ready content (Hindi / English) - see open question in section 8.

### Non-Goals (initial release)
- No citizen login, application submission, or payment flows (link out to official portals via `externalLink`).
- No multi-tenant / multi-district support (Raipur only).
- No comment system or user-generated content.

## 3. Category Taxonomy

Source of truth: `ProjectCtg.xlsx` (8 category columns, 85 unique schemes; one duplicate "Aao Khud Ko Parkhein" in Governance was de-duplicated). Categories are **CMS-managed** (the `categories` collection), seeded from this list. The Excel is canonical; the original brief mentioned "5 categories" - see the open decision below and the proposed 5-group consolidation.

